 Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from a barony in Aberdeenshire, which is first recorded <i>c.</i> 1180 in the form <i>Lesslyn</i>, of obscure origin. Leslie in Fife is said to be named for this place; in some cases the surname may come from there.","English: from the Middle English female personal name <i>Lecelin</i>, a double diminutive of <i>Lece</i>. See   Leece   and   Lesley  .","History: The Scottish Clan Leslie claims descent from Bartolf, a Hungarian nobleman who came to Scotland in 1068 or 1070 in the retinue of Queen Margaret. She was an English princess who had been born and brought up in Hungary and who went on to marry King Malcolm III of Scotland. Members of the clan have held several titles in the peerage of Scotland, including Earl of Rothes (from 1437)."],"variants":[{"name":"Leece","meanings":["English: from a medieval female personal name, <i>Lece</i>, a short form of <i>Lettice</i> (from Latin <i>Laetitia</i>, meaning ‘happiness, gaiety’).","English: variant of   Lees  .","Irish: shortened form of Gaelic <i>Mac Giolla Íosa</i>, Manx <i>Mac Guilley Yeesey</i> ‘son of <i>Giolla Íosa</i> (devotee or servant of Jesus)’. Ballaleece (‘Leece's farm’) in Kirk German was the family's main seat."]},{"name":"Lesslie","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Leslie  ."]},{"name":"Lesley","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: variant of   Leslie  ."]},{"name":"Laslie","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Leslie  ."]},{"name":"Lessley","meanings":["English (Norfolk): variant of   Leslie  ."]},{"name":"Lasley","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Leslie  ."]}]},{"name":"Norman","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Germanic origin, from <i>nord</i> ‘north’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’, i.e. ‘Norseman’. This name was in use in England before the Conquest, and was reinforced by its use among the Norman invaders themselves. The Normans were the inhabitants of Normandy in northern France, whose name is a reference to the Vikings who took control of the region in the 9th century. In the 11th and 12th centuries they achieved remarkable conquests, including not only Britain but also Sicily, southern Italy, and Antioch. In the Scottish Highlands it is used as the Anglicized equivalent of Tormod ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Norman Leslie Constable of Inverurie, 3rd Baron of Leslie was born about 1155, in Leslie, Aberdeenshire, Scotland as the son of Malcolm Leslie 2nd of Leslie, Lesslyn, Constable of Inverurie. He married Lady Agnes MacDougall of Lorn about 1190, in Scotland. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. He died before 1248, in his hometown."},"et":{"Abt 1155–Bef 1248":"umbes 1155–enne 1248","1110–Male":"1110–Surnud","1155–1248":"1155–1248","1157–Male":"1157–Surnud","1170–Female":"1170–Surnud","1190–1253":"1190–1253","1190–Male":"1190–Surnud","1200–1253":"1200–1253","1071–1176":"1071–1176","1190":"1190","about 1190":"umbes 1190","1176":"1176","1253":"1253","1110":"1110","Bef 1248":"enne 1248","1071":"1071","1170":"1170","1248":"1248","1157":"1157","Abt 1155":"umbes 1155","1200":"1200","Abt 1176":"umbes 1176","1155":"1155","about 1200":"umbes 1200","Abt 1190":"umbes 1190","Lesslyn, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Aberdeenshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Leslie, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Leslie, Aberdeenshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland","Rathes,Moray,Scotland":"Rothes, Moray, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1155–Bef 1248":"noin 1155–ennen vuotta 1248","1110–Male":"1110–Kuollut","1155–1248":"1155–1248","1157–Male":"1157–Kuollut","1170–Female":"1170–Kuollut","1190–1253":"1190–1253","1190–Male":"1190–Kuollut","1200–1253":"1200–1253","1071–1176":"1071–1176","1190":"1190","about 1190":"noin 1190","1176":"1176","1253":"1253","1110":"1110","Bef 1248":"ennen vuotta 1248","1071":"1071","1170":"1170","1248":"1248","1157":"1157","Abt 1155":"noin 1155","1200":"1200","Abt 1176":"noin 1176","1155":"1155","about 1200":"